Jira User Story
Title: EIM: Add "EIM-" Prefix to all Issue IDs
User Story:
As a user, I want all numeric Issue IDs within the "Enterprise Issue Management" (EIM) module to be prefixed with "EIM-", so that I can immediately distinguish EIM issues from issues in other modules (like "Issues and Findings Legacy") and prevent ambiguity when referencing them.
Problem Statement:
Currently, the Issue IDs in the "Enterprise Issue Management" (EIM) module are purely numeric (e.g., 12345). Our platform also has other modules, such as "Issues and Findings Legacy," which also use numeric IDs. This creates ambiguity and a high risk of confusion.
When a user references "Issue 12345" in conversations, emails, or other documents, it is impossible to know which module it belongs to without additional context. This can lead to wasted time, communication errors, and mistakes in issue tracking. Prefixing the EIM-specific IDs with "EIM-" (e.g., EIM-12345) will provide immediate, clear context for every issue.
Acceptance Criteria (Checklist Style):
 * The "EIM-" prefix is automatically added to every Issue ID generated by the Enterprise Issue Management module.
 * The new EIM-[IssueID] format is displayed consistently across all relevant areas of the application, including:
   * Detail views (e.g., page titles, header fields)
   * List/table views
   * Search results
   * Dropdown menus for issue selection
   * Any data exports (e.g., CSV, PDF)
 * The core numeric part of the ID remains the same. For example, issue 12345 should become EIM-12345, not a new number.
 * Users must be able to search for an issue using both the full prefixed ID (EIM-12345) and the numeric part only (12345).
 * Existing Issue IDs within the EIM module are backfilled to include the "EIM-" prefix.
 * Hyperlinks to issues that were created before this change should still resolve correctly to the issue page.
Why this User Story is Effective:
 * Clear Purpose: The "so that" clause in the user story immediately tells the developer the goal: to distinguish between issue types.
 * Strong Justification: The problem statement outlines a real-world business scenario (referencing an issue in an email) to highlight the negative impact of not making this change.
 * Comprehensive Requirements: The acceptance criteria cover all angles: where the change should appear, how search should function, and critically, how to handle existing data (backfilled) and existing links (hyperlinks). This thoroughness prevents ambiguity during development and testing.
